985
01:55:05,166 --> 01:55:10,728
but all principal structures would need to be at least 15 feet apart from one another.

986
01:55:11,448 --> 01:55:15,289
Currently on the site, there are nine structures on the site.

987
01:55:15,629 --> 01:55:19,351
There's residential buildings, a small garage, and the community center.

988
01:55:20,871 --> 01:55:32,315
It is my understanding that there's a recent amendment or a proposed amendment that postdates our application that is now supposed to allow for multiple

989
01:55:33,734 --> 01:55:36,357
buildings on in an apartment one district.

990
01:55:37,338 --> 01:55:41,141
But I haven't, I'm unclear on the status of that.

991
01:55:41,262 --> 01:55:48,709
So for the purposes of our amendment, we continue to include that provision so that we can have the multiple buildings on this site.

992
01:55:50,397 --> 01:56:04,140
As Natalie described in her presentation, we are through this PDD increasing the density at the site in order to allow us to achieve the objectives of creating more affordable housing.

993
01:56:04,980 --> 01:56:06,440
What does that look like?

994
01:56:07,480 --> 01:56:13,381
It looks like that our minimum lot area, though the base is 10,000 square feet,

995
01:56:16,978 --> 01:56:21,842
in an apartment one, it then is really calculated based on dwelling units.

996
01:56:22,342 --> 01:56:38,254
And we would allow for 750 square feet per dwelling unit rather than what would be generated kind of through a formula that you have in your zoning that would generate a requirement of 940.

997
01:56:39,975 --> 01:56:49,119
square feet per dwelling unit for development of the size that we would be proposing here, which is 238 units.

998
01:56:49,860 --> 01:57:02,286
The other element of density to note here is also that the maximum lot coverage, we are proposing that maximum lot coverage would be 35 percent.

999
01:57:05,706 --> 01:57:15,752
The design puts our lot coverage actually at 30%, which is also what is in an apartment one district.

1000
01:57:16,393 --> 01:57:22,816
But here we've done that to just allow for some flexibility in the design.

1001
01:57:23,717 --> 01:57:30,901
The other two pieces of density that I just want to call out to the board relates to open space.

1002
01:57:31,405 --> 01:57:39,348
The landscaped open space would be 10% in this PDD, and it is 10% in an apartment one district.

1003
01:57:40,629 --> 01:57:49,493
The usable open space, given the way in which we will reconfigure the development, will be 10% as well of the gross floor area.

1004
01:57:49,993 --> 01:57:53,754
And this usable space, though lower than the 25%

1005
01:57:56,296 --> 01:58:07,603
that is in an apartment one district actually will be as designed, more accessible, and in fact, more usable than the existing open space that's on the site.

1006
01:58:09,685 --> 01:58:15,428
I think the other density piece, Natalie, can you go to the next slide?

1007
01:58:15,468 --> 01:58:18,611
Because I think we should talk about height and stories.

1008
01:58:21,456 --> 01:58:26,078
This PDD3 has two uses that we are proposing.

1009
01:58:26,819 --> 01:58:34,102
One is multiple dwelling, class A and class B. Another use is attached single family dwellings.

1010
01:58:34,343 --> 01:58:36,664
And so height is correlated to those uses.

1011
01:58:37,224 --> 01:58:44,788
So for multiple dwellings, we are looking at maximum of 75 feet and six stories.

1012
01:58:46,288 --> 01:58:53,350
And for the attached single-family dwellings, we are looking at a maximum height of 35 and three stories.

1013
01:58:54,511 --> 01:59:05,534
In an apartment one district, where attached single-family dwellings height in stories is the same as is being proposed in this PDD.

1014
01:59:06,994 --> 01:59:15,357
And as I mentioned before, only multiple dwelling class A's are currently permitted within an apartment one district.

1015
01:59:17,633 --> 01:59:32,421
